tical and ecoGothic investigation of uncanny manifestations in gardens – hauntings, psychic encounters, monstrous hybrids, fairies and ghosts – with plants, greenhouses, granges, mansions, lakes, lawns, flowerbeds and trees as agents and sites of uncanny developments. The collection represents the forefront of ecoGothic critical debate and will be welcomed by specialists in environmental humanities at every level, as a timely, innovative inclusion in ecoGothic studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEcocriticism. 0aGardens in literature. 0aGothic fiction (Literary genre)xHistory and criticism. 0aNature in literature. 4aGothic 2021. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aagency.  aecoGothic.  aecocriticism.  aecomaterialism.  aecophobia.  agardens.  aninteenth century.  aplants.  auncanny.  avegetal.1 aBihet, Francesca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrosby, Joanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdney, Sue, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdney, Sue, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEvans, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFitzpatrick, Teresa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeholt, Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHughes, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIkin, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSaguaro, Shelley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScott, Christopher M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/